SIMPLE: glacial
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glacial
<hw>Gla"cial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>glacialis</ets>, from <ets>glacies</ets> ice: cf. F.
<ets>glacial</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to ice or to its
action; consisting of ice; frozen; icy; esp., pertaining to glaciers;
<as>as, <ex>glacial</ex> phenomena</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Resembling ice; having the
appearance and consistency of ice; -- said of certain solid compounds;
<as>as, <ex>glacial</ex> phosphoric or acetic acids</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Glacial acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>an acid of
such strength or purity as to crystallize at an ordinary temperature, in
an icelike form; as acetic or carbolic acid.</cd> -- <col><b>Glacial
drift</b></col> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>earth and rocks which have been
transported by moving ice, land ice, or icebergs; bowlder drift.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Glacial epoch</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Glacial
period</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Geol.)</fld>, <cd>a period during which
the climate of the modern temperate regions was polar, and ice covered
large portions of the northern hemisphere to the mountain tops.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Glacial theory</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Glacial
hypothesis</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Glacier
theory</cref>, under <er>Glacier</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glacialist</ent>⟦br⟧
